In parenthetic clauses like this, the introductory ut may convey two very different meanings according to the context. Thus in Acad. 2. 98 homo acutus, ut Poenus is ‘a keen-witted man, as mig-ht be expected of a Carthaginian ’ (cf. Colum. 1, 3, 8 acutissimam gentem Poenos) while Nepos, Epam. 5, 2
